### 8. Exception Handling in Test
**Smell:** Manual `try`/`catch` instead of MSTest's `Assert.ThrowsException<T>`. The `Assert.Fail` call is easy to forget; if omitted, the test passes when no exception is thrown.
**Location:** `ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsValidationError` (lines 110–118)

```csharp
// ❌ Current — manual exception management
try
{
    processor.ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.Fail("Expected an exception but none was thrown");
}
catch (ValidationException ex)
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
}
```

**Fix:** Use the framework's built-in mechanism:
```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ValidationException>(
    () => processor.ProcessOrder(order));
Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
```
**Risk if unfixed:** If `Assert.Fail` is accidentally removed, the test silently passes when no exception is thrown.

